uales de dos traductores estadounidenses: Alice Stone Blackwell e Isaac Goldberg. Su audiencia son académicos, profesores y estudiantes de estudios de traducción y estudios latinoamericanos y hemisféricos en general. Sus contribuciones más importantes son la historización, conceptualización y análisis de la figura del traductor amateur como un sujeto de resistencia y el ser el primer estudio dedicado a pensar la figura y narrar la historia moderna del traductor amateur como instancia de mediación cultural entre Estados Unidos y América Latina.  aThis book analyzes, conceptualizes and historicizes the amateur translator figure as political and cultural agent in US-Latin American relations, from the end of the 19th century to the mid-20th century. Centered on the work of two US-American translators, Alice Stone Blackwell and Isaac Goldberg, it is the first study to offer a modern history of the amateur translator as subject of resistance and cultural mediator between the two regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn Spanish, Castilian.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLatin American literaturexTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aGoldberg, Isaac. 4aStone Blackwell, Alice. 4aUS-lateinamerikanische Beziehungen. 4aliterarische Übersetzung. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aGoldberg, Isaac.  aLiterary translation.  aStone Blackwell, Alice.  aUS-Latin American relations.0 cEPUBz97831107501020 cprintz978311074964940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110749984zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110749984zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110749984/original  aGB